# speckit Constitution: richards_sudoku

## Code Quality
- Preserve modular boundaries: generation, solving, UI, persistence, statistics, and SE difficulty grading must remain decoupled with clear interfaces and no cross-layer side effects.
- Enforce readability: prefer explicit logic over clever shortcuts; include concise comments only for non-obvious algorithms (solver, generator, SE technique logic, jigsaw/Str8ts/Killer rules).
- Use typing and validation: type-hint public functions, validate inputs for puzzle size/variant, and fail fast on invalid states.
- Serialization discipline: JSON save/load/import/export must be versioned and backward compatible; reject malformed payloads safely. Schema version must be incremented whenever the save format gains new fields (e.g. `se_score`/`se_label`).
- Determinism for reproducibility: generators accept seeds; solver behavior remains stable across runs and OSes.
- SE engine extensibility: adding a new solving technique requires only (a) implementing a class with a `name`, `weight`, and `apply(grid) -> bool` interface and (b) inserting it into `_TECHNIQUES` at the correct weight position — no other changes needed. Never hardcode technique count or weight values outside `difficulty_se.py`.

## Testing Standards
- Unit tests cover solver correctness, generator validity (unique/solvable), persistence round-trips (save -> load, including se_score/se_label round-trip), and stats tracking (timer/moves/hints).
- SE difficulty grader tests: boundary scores for `score_to_label`; `grade()` on known-difficulty fixtures; per-technique minimal fixture (one test per technique class); variant paths (Str8ts run, Killer cage); performance guard (< 100ms for 9×9).
- Property-based or scenario suites exercise multiple grid sizes and variants (Standard, Jigsaw, Str8ts, Killer, 1–25, Codewords, KenKen, Kakuro) with conflict/constraint checks.
- UI smoke tests verify grid rendering, selection, highlight behaviors, undo/redo, hint availability, and pencil mark visibility for each variant.
- Regression harness for import/export: known fixtures must load, validate solvability, and remain playable end-to-end.
- Performance guards: add tests/benchmarks for solver/runtime budgets to prevent slowdowns; enforce deterministic seeds in tests.

## User Experience Consistency
- Grid UX: always highlight selected cell, row, column, and region; pencil marks visually distinct from confirmed entries across themes and variants.
- Controls parity: keyboard/mouse inputs, undo/redo, hint trigger, and pencil toggle behave the same for all variants and grid sizes.
- Accessibility and theming: provide light/dark themes, adjustable font sizes, and readable contrast; avoid color-only cues for conflicts.
- Persistence UX: save/load/import/export flows are discoverable, confirm success/failure, and never discard user progress without explicit consent.
- Guidance and feedback: in-game help and hint usage counts are visible; conflicts and invalid moves are clearly indicated without blocking navigation.

## Performance Requirements
- Solver and validator complete typical 9x9 puzzles within interactive latency targets (<200ms for validation, <2s for solve) and scale gracefully for larger grids.
- UI remains responsive during generation/solve via background work or progress cues; no frozen input during long operations.
- Save/load/import/export operations complete quickly (<300ms for typical puzzles) and are atomic to prevent data loss.
- Memory usage stays bounded for large variants ; avoid quadratic blowups in candidate tracking and undo/redo history.
